04558nam a22007335i 9780823291250DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20222013nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232912507 a10.1515/97808232912502doi  a(DE-B1597)566068  a(OCoLC)1306540869  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aHIS0360502bisacsh00aConstitutionalism in the Approach and Aftermath of the Civil War /ced. by Paul D. Moreno, Johnathan O'Neill. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b9 Illustrations, black and white  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe North's Civil War0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe irreducibly constitutional nature of the Civil War’s prelude and legacy is the focus of this absorbing collection of nine essays by a diversity of political theorists and historians. The contributors examine key constitutional developments leading up to the war, the crucial role of Abraham Lincoln’s statesmanship, and how the constitutional aspects of the war and Reconstruction endured in the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries. This thoughtful, informative volume covers a wide range of topics: from George Washington’s conception of the Union and his fears for its future to Martin Van Buren’s state-centered, anti-secessionist federalism; from Lincoln’s approach to citizenship for African Americans to Woodrow Wilson’s attempt to appropriate Lincoln for the goals of Progressivism. Each essay zeroes in on the constitutional causes or consequences of the war and emphasizes how constitutional principles shape political activity. Accordingly, important figures, disputes, and judicial decisions are placed within the broader context of the constitutional system to explain how ideas and institutions, independently and in dialogue with the courts, have oriented political action and shaped events over time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 7aHISTORY / United States / Civil War Period (1850-1877).2bisacsh1 aBelz, Herman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenedict, Michael Les, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEsh, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFornieri, Joseph R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoreno, Paul D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoreno, Paul D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMorrison, Jeffry H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO'Neill, Johnathan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aO’Neill, Johnathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPestritto, Ronald J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWhite, Jonathan W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311070729840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082329125040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823291250423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823291250/original  a978-3-11-070729-8  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK